  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strengthening Resilience of the Most Vulnerable in Rakhine and Shan States Through Provision of Protection and Health Services and Improvement of Emergency Preparedness</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">RI offers immediate and lifesaving health and protection services for IDPs and surrounding communities in Rakhine and Shan States, while also helping to strengthen the resilience of communities by building capacity to mitigate future shocks.
In Rakhine State, RI delivers primary, maternal and psychosocial health services in two IDP camps (Taung Paw [Muslim] and Khan Thar Htwat Wa [Rakhine]) and surrounding communities in Myebon township. In addition to ongoing IDP support, RI extended some services including Protection and Health to non-displaced conflict-affected and `hard to reach&apos; communities in Rakhine in order to meet their needs and avoid exacerbating tensions between host communities and IDPs.
In Southern Shan, the October 2015 armed conflict between the government military and the Shan State Army North (SSPP/SSA-N) left 6,000 people displaced, from across 25 villages. RI continues its response to supporting those displaced by the conflict of October 2015 through the implementation of Emergency Preparedness Plans for field staff and partners in anticipation of further violence, displacement and IDPs; and the purchasing of contingency stocks for IDPs in anticipation of further displacement.</narrative>
  </description>
